Hence, orthogonal vectors always remain orthogonal under parallel transport. Since all the eigenvalues of an isotropic tensor are equal, the cube formed by the eigenpairs $\{\lambda\boldsymbol{a},\lambda\boldsymbol{b},\lambda\boldsymbol{c}\}$, where $\{\boldsymbol{a},\boldsymbol{b},\boldsymbol{c}\}$ are any triple of orthonormal vectors forming the eigenspace of $\boldsymbol{q}$ (any orthonormal triple of vectors forms the eigenspace of an isotropic tensor), becomes an inflated/deflated cube as one moves along the curve $\mathcal{C}$ (see Figure \ref{irrot_and_iso}(b)). The auxiliary material space for isotropic metric anomalies is conformal to the original material space, because $\bar{\boldsymbol{g}}=(1+2\lambda)\boldsymbol{g}$.
